Cheung Kong, Hyundai Heavy, NTPM: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-09-25T22:05:18Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-25/cheung-kong-hyundai-heavy-ntpm-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Cheung Kong  (Holdings) Ltd. (1 HK): Chairman  Li Ka-shing 
bought 340,000 shares of the company at an average HK$93.77 each
on Sept. 21, according to a disclosure filing to the Hong Kong
stock exchange. Cheung Kong, a property developer, declined 1
percent to HK$88.60.  Global-Estate Resorts Inc. (GERI PM): The company’s
director approved an increase in its authorized capital stock to
20 billion pesos ($459 million) from 10 billion pesos, a stock-
exchange filing showed. Global-Estate Resorts, a Philippine
property developer, sank 8.9 percent to 2.05 pesos.  Hanjin Shipping Co. (117930 KS):  South Korea ’s largest
shipping line plans to sell its entire stake in unlisted unit
Hanjin Energy Co. for 159.8 billion won ($137 million) to
improve liquidity and to meet local antitrust rules about
holding companies, the Seoul-based company said in a regulatory
filing. Hanjin Shipping plunged 15 percent to 13,700 won.  Hyundai Heavy Industries Co. (009540 KS): The world’s
largest shipyard said new orders in the January-August period
climbed 57 percent from a year earlier to $20.3 billion,
according to a regulatory filing. Sales in August rose 9.7
percent to 1.99 trillion won, the filing said. Hyundai Heavy
Industries fell 8.1 percent to 266,000 won.  International Container Terminal Services Inc. (ICT)  :
ICTSI Warehousing Inc., a subsidiary of the largest Philippine
port operator, bought 4.5 million shares of the company in the
open market, a stock-exchange filing showed. The stock decreased
2.2 percent to 49 pesos.  NTPM Holdings Bhd. (NTPM)  : The Malaysian tissue-paper
maker’s profit in the first quarter ended July 31 fell 26
percent from a year earlier to 9.23 million ringgit ($2.9
million), according to a company statement. NTPM advanced 1.9
percent to 53 sen.  SK Networks Co. (001740 KS): The South Korean trading
company is considering an investment in Cockatoo Coal Ltd. and
is in talks with the Australian company over terms, according to
a regulatory filing by the South Korean company. SK Networks
tumbled 8 percent to 10,300 won.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
